<font color="#FF0000">DRAFT EVADERS, AGAIN</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb 16 18:08:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Terry Crenshaw<br>
At one time I took refuge in the thought because I volunteered for the draft, that someone else didn't have to go.  I don't think this works for me anymore.  In the same light, I can understand how some would believe, because some &quot;ran away&quot;, others had to take there place, that didn't need to go.<br><br>
Personally, I think both arguments are a wash, an non-issue.<br><br>
Arthur and Pointman - If those that left the country were &quot;cowards&quot;, would you have wanted them in the bush side by side with you, providing you with the backup, the support that each of us depended on just to stay alive?  <br><br>
Terry - I am encouraged knowing about that museum in Germany.  I can understand the reasons for so few names.  Those that resisted were shot or hanged!  Those that resisted then showed much courage.  The &quot;strong moral sense&quot; that you speak of I question.  How many of those that left the country did so because of moral outrage, versus those that left because of the fear that it would interrupt their pusuit of the American dream?  How many left because of the fear of the war itself and the prospects of dying?<br><br>
Again, I don't need a response.  It's another non-issue.
